{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 20:31:36.196151", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='OSPF Routing Process, Router ID: 172.16.0.3\\n Supports only single TOS (TOS0) routes\\n This implementation conforms to RFC2328\\n RFC1583Compatibility flag is disabled\\n OpaqueCapability flag is disabled\\n Initial SPF scheduling delay 0 millisec(s)\\n Minimum hold time between consecutive SPFs 50 millisec(s)\\n Maximum hold time between consecutive SPFs 5000 millisec(s)\\n Hold time multiplier is currently 1\\n SPF algorithm last executed 39.712s ago\\n Last SPF duration 156 usecs\\n SPF timer is inactive\\n LSA minimum interval 5000 msecs\\n LSA minimum arrival 1000 msecs\\n Write Multiplier set to 20 \\n Refresh timer 10 secs\\n Maximum multiple paths(ECMP) supported 256\\n Administrative distance 110\\n Number of external LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x00000000\\n Number of opaque AS LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x00000000\\n Number of areas attached to this router: 1\\n Area ID: 0.0.0.0 (Backbone)\\n   Number of interfaces in this area: Total: 3, Active: 3\\n   Number of fully adjacent neighbors in this area: 3\\n   Area has no authentication\\n   SPF algorithm executed 14 times\\n   Number of LSA 16\\n   Number of router LSA 4. Checksum Sum 0x00019fe7\\n   Number of network LSA 4. Checksum Sum 0x00030a4c\\n   Number of summary LSA 8. Checksum Sum 0x00043507\\n   Number of ASBR summary LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x00000000\\n   Number of NSSA LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x00000000\\n   Number of opaque link LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x00000000\\n   Number of opaque area LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x00000000' name='frr_get_ospf_conf' id='47988216-c5e3-40b3-903c-d91b5693439c' tool_call_id='call_5ekq9akLz5zgsclPUyIKkD29'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 20:32:43.569869", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network health and anomalies\n\nSummary (top-level)\n- The network is largely healthy and functioning: OSPF has converged across core/distribution/server routers, DHCP and DNS servers are reachable from user hosts, and the public server farm (10.200.0.0/24) and the load-balancer (10.200.0.7) are reachable from access hosts. There is no packet loss on the user-to-infrastructure and intra-server pings observed; interface states are UP on routers/switches/hosts.\n- One noteworthy deviation from full connectivity: the backend web network (20.200.0.0/24 — backend_web_0/1/2) is not reachable from the user host subnets (10.x.x.x). This isolation appears in the reachability matrix and in routing tables.\n\nFindings and evidence\n\n1) OSPF and routing state\n- OSPF is up and populated on the FRR routers (router_core_1/2/3, server_access_router, dist routers). Routing tables on multiple cores and the server-access router show 10.200.0.0/24 (server farm) is known and reachable via the server-access router.\n  - Example: router_core_1 has 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.3 (router_core_3) in its table.\n- There is no advertised route (in the examined router tables) for the 20.200.0.0/24 network. The routers’ route outputs show 10.200.0.0/24 but not 20.200.0.0/24.\n\n2) Host addressing, DHCP, DNS\n- Access hosts successfully obtained addresses via DHCP (examples: host_1_1_1_1 = 10.1.1.11, host_2_1_1_1 = 10.2.1.10). Their default routes point to the local distribution routers.\n- DHCP server (10.200.0.8) and DNS server (10.200.0.2) are reachable from access hosts (pings show 0% loss, low RTT). Example: from many hosts ping -> dns_server (10.200.0.2) succeeded with small RTTs.\n- server_access_router has 10.200.0.1 and is connected/announcing 10.200.0.0/24.\n\n3) Web farm and load balancer connectivity\n- Load balancer: has two addresses — 10.200.0.7 (public-facing) and 20.200.0.1 (backend-facing). Access hosts can reach the load balancer at 10.200.0.7 (ping success from many hosts).\n- The web servers in 10.200.0.0/24 (web_server_0..3 at 10.200.0.3–6) are reachable from hosts (pings successful).\n- The backend web servers on 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_0..2 at 20.200.0.2–4) are reachable from the load balancer and other backend nodes, but pings from user/access hosts to those 20.200.0.x addresses show status \"unknown\" (no reachability).\n\n4) Ping/reachability matrix highlights\n- From many user hosts: pings to 10.200.0.2–8 (DNS, web servers, DHCP, load balancer public IP) all successful with 0% packet loss.\n- From user hosts: pings to backend_web_0/1/2 (20.200.0.x) are \"unknown\" (unreachable).\n- From backend and load_balancer: backend web hosts (20.200.0.x) can communicate with load_balancer (20.200.0.1) and among themselves (pings successful), indicating the backend network functions inside its segment.\n\nAnomalies (localized)\n- Anomaly: 20.200.0.0/24 (backend web network) is not reachable/visible from the access host subnets (10.x.x.x).\n  - Affected devices/subnets: backend_web_0, backend_web_1, backend_web_2 (20.200.0.2–4) are not reachable from any access hosts tested.\n  - Evidence:\n    - Reachability matrix: user-host -> backend_web_* entries are \"unknown\" (no successful pings).\n    - Routing tables on core/distribution routers do not show a route for 20.200.0.0/24, while 10.200.0.0/24 is present and reachable.\n  - Localized to: lack of network advertisement/routing (20.200.0.0/24) beyond the load-balancer/backend segment (i.e., the backend net is only locally known to the load_balancer and backend hosts).\n\nRoot-cause hypothesis (what explains the observed anomaly)\n- The backend network (20.200.0.0/24) is isolated from the rest of the network — it is present and functional locally (load_balancer eth1 and backend nodes have 20.200.0.x addresses and can communicate among themselves) but it is not present in the global routing tables on the core/distribution routers.\n- Two plausible explanations (consistent with observations and topology):\n  1) Intentional isolation: the backend network is deliberately not advertised into OSPF (or filtered) so that access hosts cannot directly reach backend servers — this aligns with the design statement that backend servers should not be directly accessible from hosts. Evidence supporting intentional isolation: load balancer has both 10.200.0.7 and 20.200.0.1 and backend nodes can reach LB while user hosts cannot reach 20.200.0.x.\n  2) Unadvertised/misadvertised network: the server-access device (or FRR configuration) is not advertising 20.200.0.0/24 into OSPF, so upstream routers have no route to that network. Evidence: absence of 20.200.0.0/24 entries in core/distribution routing tables despite 10.200.0.0/24 being present.\n- The data (reachability + routing tables) indicate that the lack of route advertisement for 20.200.0.0/24 is the immediate technical cause of the observed unreachability from access subnets.\n\nOther observations (non-failures)\n- Interfaces and links show UP, OSPF neighbor counts are reasonable, and no packet loss is observed on core/distribution/server pings; RTTs are low and stable in most cases. Some individual RTT mdevs are high in isolated cases in the ping matrix, but these are intermittent and not correlated with packet loss or routing failures.\n- Some addresses use .0 in /31s (e.g., router_core_1 eth0 = 172.16.0.0/31). /31 addressing is valid for point-to-point links; no operational errors observed from that.\n\nSummary — impact and root cause\n- Impact: User hosts (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24) cannot directly reach backend web servers in 20.200.0.0/24. Other services (DHCP, DNS, public web servers in 10.200.0.0/24, and load-balancer 10.200.0.7) are reachable and appear operational.\n- Root cause: The backend network 20.200.0.0/24 is not present in the global routing tables (not advertised or intentionally isolated) — resulting in lack of reachability from access subnets. This matches either a deliberate security/isolation policy or a routing advertisement/configuration omission at the server-access/load-balancer side.\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- (a) verify FRR/OSPF advertisement of 20.200.0.0/24 on server_access_router and load_balancer, and/or\n- (b) run targeted traceroutes from access hosts to backend_web addresses to show where packets are dropped.\n\n(Those are offered only for further diagnosis; no mitigation steps are included per your request.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 62120, "output_tokens": 4346, "total_tokens": 66466, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 3072}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2624}}}
